Summary : Can you predict fraud based off a plethera of data? When seeing this data, I immediately focused on TF2.0 to handle this. Utilizing different techniques to clean data I arrived of a model accuracy of .9225, sadly winners were around .955 ~

What I learned:

All the top submitters were using Lightgbm, something I've never heard of (something that I will have to take a look at)

All the top submitters heavily focused on feature scaling, something I left out because of a bad assumption that all variables would be relevant.

Many of the top submitters didn't utilize dummy variables, which I will have to look more into, maybe this could be the difference of the .032 % I was off.

Better luck next time!

Model¶

In [62]:
#Hyperparameters
input_size = 100
output_size = 2
hidden_layer_size = 120

# Sequential used to start layering the model (STACK LAYERS)

model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(hidden_layer_size, activation='tanh'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(hidden_layer_size, activation='elu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(output_size, activation='softmax'),
                            
                            ])

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

EPOCHS = 100
BATCH_SIZE = 1000


early_stopping = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='loss', patience=3)

model.fit(train,
         test,
         batch_size = BATCH_SIZE,
         epochs = EPOCHS,
        callbacks=[early_stopping],
         verbose = 2)
